{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nMake the `rebar metrics` surface (this epic's registry + `rebar metrics` command) **usable by the tools that do code-health work, and discoverable in project docs** — so the metrics are not a dead-end artifact. Two deliverables: (1) teach the **rebar-janitor** skill to consult `rebar metrics` as durable, historical code-health evidence during Discovery; (2) reference the metrics surface from the project's canonical documentation so any agent/contributor can find it.\n\n## Why\nThe janitor's Discovery phase already quantifies \"size & growth\" and \"temporal decay\" with one-shot tools (`cloc`/`tokei`/`ast-grep`, `git log`). `rebar metrics` adds the **trend** dimension those miss — the code-health-lens metrics the registry actually ships: the registered code-health-lens metrics — module-size distribution, oversized-module count and the module-size trend against the locked 800-line cap, short-term churn, the refactor-to-addition ratio, and cap-change events — as a single durable source. (Complexity/clone/coverage snapshots exist in the store but are not yet surfaced by a registered metric, so they do not appear in `rebar metrics` output — do not cite them.) A janitor that cites `rebar metrics` values as evidence produces findings grounded in measured decay over time, not just a single snapshot. And metrics no agent knows to read provide no value, so discoverability (docs) is part of \"done\".\n\n## Files\n- `examples/agent-skills/rebar-janitor/phases/discovery.md` — in the \"Size & growth\" / temporal-decay guidance, add that a subagent should run `rebar metrics --since <date> --until <date> --output json` (when the repo is a rebar store) and cite the registered code-health-lens metric values (module-size distribution, oversized-module count and module-size trend vs the 800 cap, churn, refactor-to-addition ratio, cap-change events) as evidence; a metric whose signal has not accrued reads `unavailable` — as the historical/trend complement to the one-shot `cloc`/`tokei`/`ast-grep` pass, not a replacement. Note the `unavailable` state (a metric whose signal has not accrued yet) so the agent does not treat absence as zero.\n- `docs/user-guide.md` — add a short, hand-written **\"Metrics\"** section: what `rebar metrics --since/--until [--output json]` surfaces (the four lenses — `agent_process`, `code_health`, `delivery`, `gate_economics`), the `source`/`confidence` labels and the `unavailable{reason,accruing_since}` state, and that backfilled/classified values are segregated from authoritative structural series. This is the human-discoverable home (the CLI-reference is auto-generated syntax; this is the \"what/why/when\").\n- `docs/reuse-surface.md` — reference the reusable `rebar.metrics` subsystem (the `MetricSpec`/`REGISTRY` declarative registry + `is_authoritative` segregation helper) so library consumers discover it.\n- `AGENTS.md` — add ONE line to the \"Where to read\" pointer list: **Metrics** → `docs/user-guide.md` (command + lenses) and `docs/reuse-surface.md` (the registry), keeping the file lean per its own convention.\n\n## Approach\nDocumentation- and skill-only; no `src/rebar` change and no new behavior — it makes the already-shipped `rebar metrics` command and registry usable and findable. It stacks on the metrics command (9a5a) so it references the command's real, landed interface (and so `docs/cli-reference.md` already lists the subcommand). Additive and reversible (revert = remove the references).\n\n## Tests\n- Doc/skill assertions (no runtime code): a check that `examples/agent-skills/rebar-janitor/phases/discovery.md` mentions `rebar metrics`; that `docs/user-guide.md` has a Metrics section naming the four lens values (agent_process/code_health/delivery/gate_economics) and the `unavailable` state; that `AGENTS.md`'s \"Where to read\" list has a metrics pointer; that `docs/reuse-surface.md` references `rebar.metrics`. (These can be a lightweight `tests/scripts/`-tier grep test or folded into the existing docs-index/README drift checks.)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `examples/agent-skills/rebar-janitor/phases/discovery.md` instructs a Discovery subagent to consult `rebar metrics --since <date> --until <date> --output json` for the code-health lens and cite its values as evidence — verified by a grep/test asserting the `rebar metrics` reference and the `unavailable`-state caveat are present.\n- [ ] `docs/user-guide.md` contains a \"Metrics\" section documenting the `rebar metrics` command, the four lenses (`agent_process` / `code_health` / `delivery` / `gate_economics`), and the `source`+`confidence` labels + `unavailable` state — asserted by a grep/test for the section heading and the lens names.\n- [ ] `AGENTS.md`'s \"Where to read\" list contains a metrics pointer into `docs/` — asserted by a grep/test.\n- [ ] `docs/reuse-surface.md` references the `rebar.metrics` registry subsystem — asserted by a grep/test.\n- [ ] the docs-index / README drift gates still pass (no stale generated docs) after the edits."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784467480170888001,"uuid":"53041cab-05ef-42bf-b4d5-eb53aadf704f"}